05123nam a22007575i 9780813574417DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20162016nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97808135744177 a10.36019/97808135744172doi  a(DE-B1597)529813  a(OCoLC)952070849  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aRA644.P9bM39 2016 7aSCI0000002bisacsh04a614.5/4909732231 aMawdsley, Stephen E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSelling Science :bPolio and the Promise of Gamma Globulin /cStephen E. Mawdsley. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (232 p.) :b14 photographs, 3 maps, 4 figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCritical Issues in Health and Medicine00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. Forging Momentum -- tChapter 2. Building Consent for a Clinical Trial -- tChapter 3. Marketing and Mobilization -- tChapter 4. The Pilot Study -- tChapter 5. Operation Marbles and Lollipops -- tChapter 6. The National Experiment -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aToday, when many parents seem reluctant to have their children vaccinated, even with long proven medications, the Salk vaccine trial, which enrolled millions of healthy children to test an unproven medical intervention, seems nothing short of astonishing. In Selling Science, medical historian Stephen E. Mawdsley recounts the untold story of the first large clinical trial to control polio using healthy children—55,000 healthy children—revealing how this long-forgotten incident cleared the path for Salk’s later trial. Mawdsley describes how, in the early 1950s, Dr. William Hammon and the National Foundation for Infantile Paralysis launched a pioneering medical experiment on a previously untried scale. Conducted on over 55,000 healthy children in Texas, Utah, Iowa, and Nebraska, this landmark study assessed the safety and effectiveness of a blood component, gamma globulin, to prevent paralytic polio. The value of the proposed experiment was questioned by many prominent health professionals as it harbored potential health risks, but as Mawdsley points out, compromise and coercion moved it forward. And though the trial returned dubious results, it was presented to the public as a triumph and used to justify a federally sanctioned mass immunization study on thousands of families between 1953 and 1954. Indeed, the concept, conduct, and outcome of the GG study were sold to health professionals, medical researchers, and the public at each stage. At a time when most Americans trusted scientists, their mutual encounter under the auspices of conquering disease was shaped by politics, marketing, and at times, deception. Drawing on oral history interviews, medical journals, newspapers, meeting minutes, and private institutional records, Selling Science sheds light on the ethics of scientific conduct, and on the power of marketing to shape public opinion about medical experimentation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aChildrenxDiseaseszUnited StatesxPreventionxHistoryy20th century. 0aClinical trialszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aGamma globulinsxResearchzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aPoliomyelitisxResearchzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aPoliomyelitiszUnited StatesxPreventionxHistoryy20th century. 0aScience - Economic aspects - History - 20th century. 0aSciencexEconomic aspectsxHistoryy20th century. 0aSciencexSocial aspectsxHistoryy20th century. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh0 cprintz978081357439440uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978081357441